What you&#39;re trying to do isn&#39;t directly possible, however it isn&#39;t best pattern either. If your intent is to only allow access to the `majorId` string, you have a couple clean options:

1. Deconstruction in constructor

By passing the Major object in your constructor you can fetch its id for local usage:
```java
public class Student {
  public final String majorId;
  
  public Student(Major m) {
    this.majorId = m.majorId;
  }
}
```
or, pass the id by itself:
```java
  ...
  public Student(String majorId) { 
    this.majorId = majorId 
  }
```

2. Access level definition

In theory there&#39;s not much benefit to avoiding keeping the `Major` object reference in the `Student` class. You can make the major private and only allow access to the majorId value. Really, this is a getter, but it&#39;s good pattern.

```java
public class Student {
  private final Major major;

  public Student(Major m) {
    this.major = m;
  }

  public String majorId() {
    return major.majorId;
  }
}
```

